{
  "text": "Severe hyperemesis gravidarum (SHG) is usually defined as the presence of at least 1 of the following features: ketonuria, increased blood urea, increased hematocrit, and abnormal electrolytes [CITATION_1] . Other authors identify SHG by the presence of intractable vomiting during pregnancy associated with dehydration and electrolyte and/or metabolic disturbances as well as a weight loss Ն5% [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Some women require enteral (via a nasogastric tube) or total iv nutrition [CITATION_4] . SHG is associated with considerable maternal stress and may lead to posttraumatic stress disorder and other psychological effects [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Previous studies have assessed a number of maternal factors potentially associated with SHG, but no associations were found with human chorionic gonadotropin, estrogen, thyroid hormones, leptin, or immunological components [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
  "correct_citation": {
